    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:0dfa0c00-b7e3-435f-bf62-bc99469ae82f",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a bright, energetic 3-year-old girl who is brought in by her worried mother. She is small for her age but typically full of curiosity and laughter. Today, however, she appears visibly unwell — flushed, fatigued, and clinging to her mother's arms. She has a persistent productive cough that occasionally causes her to wince in discomfort, and her breathing is noticeably rapid and labored, with mild intercostal retractions visible when her shirt is lifted.\n\n{patientName} attends a local daycare center five days a week, where she loves painting, singing nursery rhymes, and playing with building blocks. She lives at home with her mother, father, and a 6-year-old brother who recently recovered from an upper respiratory tract infection. The family has a pet rabbit. The home is a mid-size apartment in an urban neighborhood with no known mold issues or tobacco smoke exposure.\n\n{patientName}'s appetite has been poor for the past four days, and she has been refusing most solid foods, accepting only small sips of juice and water. She has been sleeping restlessly due to coughing fits that worsen at night. Her mother reports a fever that began three days ago, peaking at 39.8°C, which has been partially controlled with antipyretics.\n\nOn examination, {patientName} is alert but irritable. Her skin is warm and mildly diaphoretic. Auscultation of the chest reveals decreased breath sounds and dullness to percussion at the right lower lobe, with coarse crackles audible on that side. Her lips are slightly dry and mucous membranes are pale pink, with no cyanosis noted at rest."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:1d936139-423f-4a22-b3e1-e80d41e6bfc6",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} was born at 39 weeks gestation via normal vaginal delivery with no perinatal complications. Her birth weight was 3.2 kg, and she was discharged home after 48 hours. She has met all developmental milestones appropriate for her age. Her vaccination history is up to date, including pneumococcal conjugate vaccine (PCV13), Hib, and influenza vaccines.\n\n{patientName} had one prior episode of otitis media at age 2, treated successfully with a short course of oral antibiotics. She has had no prior hospitalizations and no history of asthma, reactive airway disease, or recurrent wheezing. There is no history of aspiration events or foreign body ingestion.\n\nShe has no known chronic illnesses and is not on any regular medications. Her brother had an upper respiratory infection approximately 10 days ago, which is considered a likely index exposure. {patientName} eats a generally balanced diet and drinks pasteurized cow's milk. She has no known food or drug allergies documented in her medical record. Her growth curve has followed the 40th percentile consistently."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
